---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="Daily Water Intake: How Many Liters Should You Drink?" description="How much water should you drink daily? Amounts in liters, glasses, and ounces with factors that affect your needs." keywords="daily water intake, how much water to drink, liters per day, water consumption, hydration guide, 8 glasses of water, water intake calculator">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Volume</span>
      </nav>
      <BlogCrossLinks title="Daily Water Intake: How Many Liters Should You Drink?" />
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">July 1, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>You have probably heard the advice to "drink 8 glasses of water a day." But how much is that in litres? And is it even accurate? Here is what science actually says about daily hydration needs.</p>

      <h2>The Quick Answer</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">General guideline: 2-3 liters per day (women: ~2.7L, men: ~3.7L total water)</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">This includes water from food (~20% of intake) and other beverages</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Converting "8 Glasses" to Liters</h2>
      <p>The "8 glasses" rule assumes 8 oz glasses (about 237 mL each):</p>
      <ul>
        <li>8 × 237 mL = 1,896 mL = approximately 1.9 liters</li>
        <li>This is roughly 64 US fluid ounces or half a US gallon</li>
        <li>In metric terms, aim for about 2 liters of plain water (8 × 250 mL glasses)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Factors That Increase Your Needs</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Exercise:</strong> Add 400-800 mL (1.5-3 cups) per hour of intense activity</li>
        <li><strong>Hot weather:</strong> Increase by 500-1000 mL on very hot days</li>
        <li><strong>Altitude:</strong> Higher elevations increase water loss through breathing</li>
        <li><strong>Pregnancy/breastfeeding:</strong> Add 300-700 mL per day</li>
        <li><strong>Illness:</strong> Fever, vomiting, or diarrhoea require increased intake</li>
        <li><strong>Body size:</strong> Larger bodies need more water (roughly 30-35 mL per kg of body weight)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Signs You Are Not Drinking Enough</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Dark yellow urine (aim for pale straw colour)</li>
        <li>Headaches, especially in the afternoon</li>
        <li>Fatigue and difficulty concentrating</li>
        <li>Dry mouth and lips</li>
        <li>Infrequent urination (fewer than 4 times a day)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Practical Tips for Staying Hydrated</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Carry a marked water bottle:</strong> A 1-litre bottle makes tracking easy — refill it 2-3 times daily</li>
        <li><strong>Drink before you feel thirsty:</strong> By the time you feel thirst, you may already be mildly dehydrated</li>
        <li><strong>Front-load your intake:</strong> Drink 500 mL within an hour of waking</li>
        <li><strong>Count all fluids:</strong> Tea, coffee (in moderation), and water-rich foods all count</li>
        <li><strong>Use the pee test:</strong> Pale yellow = good hydration. Clear = possibly too much</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Can You Drink Too Much?</h2>
      <p>Yes, but it is rare. Hyponatraemia (water intoxication) occurs when you drink so much that sodium levels in your blood become dangerously diluted. This is mainly a risk for endurance athletes who drink excessively during long events. For most people, kidneys can handle up to 0.8-1.0 liters per hour.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/volume" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Volume Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/volume" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
